Since a file to be uploaded on to or downloaded from the Internet can be extremely large e.g. 4GB, the generation of the checksum is performed on a secondary thread. This ensures the UI of the program will not be blocked. However, to prevent repeated clicks on the \'93
\b Generate
\b0 \'94 button, this widget will be disabled on the first click. At the same time the \'93
\b Cancel
\b0 \'94 button will be enabled to allow the user to stop the generation process which might (in his view) taking an inordinately long time.\
\
Note: macOS applications are not files but special folders (file packages). On macOS, there are many such packages; the user should be aware of such folders. 
\b CheckSums
\b0  will not generate a check sum on a directory special or otherwise.\
\
Identification of a file package is very easy. Just control-click (right-click if the user is using a 2-button mouse) on a file on the macOS desktop. The pop-up contextual menu will have a menu item labeled \'93
\i Show Package Contents
\i0 \'94 if the file is actually a special folder.\
\
Hidden files (names of files which starts with a dot) are ignored. Symbolic links and mount points are not supported.\
\
The actual work of  generating a checksum is done by calling Apple\'92s 
\b CommonCrypto
\b0  C library. 
\b CheckSums
\b0  creates an instance of Operation which reads the file in chunks of 100 MB and passes the data to the methods of 
\b CommonCrypto
\b0 . So if 
\b option B
\b0  is chosen, there may be many tasks being run in the background. The last task will send a message to 
\b CheckSums
\b0  to write out the results to a text file. \
\
It follows that there is only 1 task  when an ordinary file is dropped onto the \'93
\b Path:
\b0 \'94 textfield. For this case, its hash value will be returned and displayed in the text field labelled \'93
\b Hash:
\b0 \'94.\
\
Warning: The textfield labelled \'93
\b Path:\'94
\b0  should be blank before dropping a file/folder onto it. \
Hint: Pressing Cmd-Z may clear the entire field. Alternatively, highlight the entire text and press Delete/Backspace/Cmd-Z.\
\
